<p>Thousands of One Direction fans endured rain, roaches and sleepless nights in New York City for a free concert by their favourite band</p><div class="author"><a href="http://www.theguardian.com/profile/amanda-holpuch">Amanda Holpuch</a></div><br/><p style="clear:both" /><img width='1' height='1' src='http://feeds.theguardian.com/c/34708/f/663879/s/30526d35/sc/10/mf.gif' border='0'/><br clear='all'/><br/><br/><a href="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/174726131822/u/53/f/663879/c/34708/s/30526d35/sc/10/rc/1/rc.htm"><img src="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/174726131822/u/53/f/663879/c/34708/s/30526d35/sc/10/rc/1/rc.img" border="0"/></a><br/><a href="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/174726131822/u/53/f/663879/c/34708/s/30526d35/sc/10/rc/2/rc.htm"><img src="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/174726131822/u/53/f/663879/c/34708/s/30526d35/sc/10/rc/2/rc.img" border="0"/></a><br/><a href="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/174726131822/u/53/f/663879/c/34708/s/30526d35/sc/10/rc/3/rc.htm"><img src="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/174726131822/u/53/f/663879/c/34708/s/30526d35/sc/10/rc/3/rc.img" border="0"/></a><br/><br/><a href="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/174726131822/u/53/f/663879/c/34708/s/30526d35/a2.htm"><img src="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/174726131822/u/53/f/663879/c/34708/s/30526d35/a2.img" border="0"/></a><img width="1" height="1" src="http://pi.feedsportal.com/r/174726131822/u/53/f/663879/c/34708/s/30526d35/a2t.img" border="0"/>
</li>
<li class="rss-item"><a class="rss-item" href="http://feeds.theguardian.com/c/34708/f/663879/s/30526d3f/sc/38/l/0L0Stheguardian0N0Cworld0C20A130Caug0C230Cchelsea0Emanning0Etransgender0Eprison0Eparis0Elees/story01.htm"  title="Prison is never easy, but transgender prisoners often face e..." target="_blank">'I hope Chelsea Manning gets the help she needs': Paris Lees, transgender former prisoner, on life inside</a> <br />
<div class="track"><img alt="" src="http://hits.theguardian.com/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.5/44460?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Achelsea-manning-transgender-prison-paris-lees%3A1955423&ch=World+news&c3=Guardian&c4=Chelsea+Manning+%28formerly+Bradley+Manning%29%2CTransgender+%28Society%29%2CUS+constitution+and+civil+liberties+%28Law%29%2CPrisons+and+probation+UK+%28Society%29%2CLaw%2CUS+news%2CUS+politics%2CCriminal+justice+UK+%28Law%29%2CSociety%2CWorld+news&c5=Society+Weekly%2CUnclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CUS+Elections%2CCommunities+Society&c6=Paris+Lees&c7=2013%2F08%2F23+07%3A45&c8=1955423&c9=Article&c10=Feature&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=%27I+hope+Chelsea+Manning+gets+the+help+she+needs%27%3A+Paris+Lees%2C+transgender+former+prisoner%2C+on+life+inside&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FWorld+news%2FChelsea+Manning+%28formerly+Bradley+Manning%29" width="1" height="1" /></div><p class="standfirst">Prison is never easy, but transgender prisoners often face extra challenges. As Chelsea Manning begins her sentence, Paris Lees recounts her experience of being trans behind bars</p><p>It turns out that they do, in fact, send people like me to prison. My friends and family assured me this wasn't so during the terrifying months leading up to my trial for robbery. Today I'm a transgender woman, but back then I was seen as a&nbsp;dangly gay boy. I'd known I was a girl since I was four, if you'll excuse the cliche, but everyone told me I&nbsp;couldn't be, because of&nbsp;a pesky penis between my legs. Puberty hit and I&nbsp;assumed I was gay. I liked boys, so what else could I call myself? I used to wear makeup and "girls' clothes" (whatever that means) because it made me happy. I supposed I&nbsp;was one of those boys who enjoyed dressing up. There are plenty of them.</p><p>It didn't feel like dressing up, though; it felt more profound than that. But how to explore that nagging feeling of being in the wrong body with the threat of prison hanging over me, too? Turn up at court wearing a suit if you want a lenient sentence, I knew that. Not that it did me any good. I borrowed a tie and got two years.</p><p>Miscarriages of justice aside, you don't end up in prison unless you've made some bad decisions. Mine was taking part in a robbery. I was 16 at the time and 18 when they locked me&nbsp;up. As you might expect, looking like a girly boy in an institute full of rough lads wasn't a barrel of&nbsp;laughs. Think Tootsie meets Scum. But prison isn't meant to be fun, is it? I got picked on, sometimes ? generally by new boys, stereotypical meat-heads who questioned my friends for "talking to that poof". It didn't happen often, though, as I&nbsp;was lucky enough to be on&nbsp;a wing for vulnerable prisoners. There wasn't much fighting but there were plenty of blood-stained sheets (and inmates) pulled out of cells after unsuccessful suicide attempts. There were successful attempts, too. Overall the boys on my wing hurt themselves, not other people, and I&nbsp;experienced more violence for being "poofy" at school than I ever did inside. I was bullied violently throughout school.</p><p>I felt divorced from myself in prison. I saw a boy who'd done stupid things and found himself in a dark place. That wasn't me, was it? I knew who I wanted to be: someone with qualifications, who didn't smoke, who ate better, who had better friends ? ones that didn't turn up in the middle of the night with decent drugs and bad ideas ? and someone who had&nbsp;managed to make that seemingly magical transition from male to female. But I doubted I could become that person. My self-esteem was crushed, back then, crouching down at the bottom of society. My dreams seemed too grand. Still, life doesn't end at 18. I knew I could try to&nbsp;change. I had nothing to lose. It was worth a go.</p><p>I had art therapy sessions, in which I&nbsp;produced crude impressions of my imagined female self. There was performance art, too, but that was a private exhibition. In my cell at night I plucked my eyebrows with my fingernails. I&nbsp;shaved daily. There's no laser hair-removal in prison. I shaved my armpits and,&nbsp;sometimes, my legs. I stole coloured chalk and ground it into crude&nbsp;makeup. I grew my hair.</p><p>Gender dysphoria is a recognised medical condition, but prisoners with&nbsp;gender issues struggle to access appropriate support. In a civil society we might remove criminals' freedom, but not their healthcare. I hope Chelsea Manning gets the help she needs.</p><div class="related" style="float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;"><ul><li><a href="http://www.theguardian.com/world/chelsea-manning">Chelsea Manning (formerly Bradley Manning)</a></li><li><a href="http://www.theguardian.com/society/transgender">Transgender</a></li><li><a href="http://www.theguardian.com/law/us-constitution-and-civil-liberties">US constitution and civil liberties</a></li><li><a href="http://www.theguardian.com/society/prisons-and-probation">Prisons and probation</a></li><li><a href="http://www.theguardian.com/world/usa">United States</a></li><li><a href="http://www.theguardian.com/world/us-politics">US politics</a></li><li><a href="http://www.theguardian.com/law/criminal-justice">UK criminal justice</a></li></ul></div><div class="author"><a href="http://www.theguardian.com/profile/paris-lees">Paris Lees</a></div><br/><div class="terms"><a href="http://www.theguardian.com">theguardian.com</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href="http://www.theguardian.com/help/terms-of-service">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href="http://www.theguardian.com/help/feeds">More Feeds</a></div><p style="clear:both" /><img width='1' height='1' src='http://feeds.theguardian.com/c/34708/f/663879/s/30526d3f/sc/38/mf.gif' border='0'/><br clear='all'/><br/><br/><a href="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/174726131821/u/53/f/663879/c/34708/s/30526d3f/sc/38/rc/1/rc.htm"><img src="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/174726131821/u/53/f/663879/c/34708/s/30526d3f/sc/38/rc/1/rc.img" border="0"/></a><br/><a href="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/174726131821/u/53/f/663879/c/34708/s/30526d3f/sc/38/rc/2/rc.htm"><img src="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/174726131821/u/53/f/663879/c/34708/s/30526d3f/sc/38/rc/2/rc.img" border="0"/></a><br/><a href="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/174726131821/u/53/f/663879/c/34708/s/30526d3f/sc/38/rc/3/rc.htm"><img src="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/174726131821/u/53/f/663879/c/34708/s/30526d3f/sc/38/rc/3/rc.img" border="0"/></a><br/><br/><a href="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/174726131821/u/53/f/663879/c/34708/s/30526d3f/a2.htm"><img src="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/174726131821/u/53/f/663879/c/34708/s/30526d3f/a2.img" border="0"/></a><img width="1" height="1" src="http://pi.feedsportal.com/r/174726131821/u/53/f/663879/c/34708/s/30526d3f/a2t.img" border="0"/>
</li>
<li class="rss-item"><a class="rss-item" href="http://feeds.theguardian.com/c/34708/f/663879/s/30526d3a/sc/11/l/0L0Stheguardian0N0Cworld0C20A130Caug0C230Cchelsea0Emanning0Etreatment0Eexpect0Ejail/story01.htm"  title="The military prison where Chelsea Manning is beginning her 3..." target="_blank">Chelsea Manning: what kind of treatment can she expect in jail?</a> <br />
<div class="track"><img alt="" src="http://hits.theguardian.com/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.5/44507?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Achelsea-manning-treatment-expect-jail%3A1955443&ch=World+news&c3=Guardian&c4=Chelsea+Manning+%28formerly+Bradley+Manning%29%2CWorld+news%2CWikiLeaks%2CEspionage+spies+spying+%28News%29%2CMedia%2CTransgender+%28Society%29%2CSociety%2CSexuality+%28Society%29%2CGender+%28News%29%2CPrisons+and+probation+UK+%28Society%29%2CCriminal+justice+UK+%28Law%29%2CUS+constitution+and+civil+liberties+%28Law%29%2CUS+news%2CLaw&c5=Society+Weekly%2CUnclassified%2CDigital+Media%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CMedia+Weekly%2CCommunities+Society&c6=Eric+Allison%2CHelen+Pidd&c7=2013%2F08%2F23+07%3A45&c8=1955443&c9=Article&c10=Feature&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Chelsea+Manning%3A+what+kind+of+treatment+can+she+expect+in+jail%3F&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FWorld+news%2FChelsea+Manning+%28formerly+Bradley+Manning%29" width="1" height="1" /></div><p class="standfirst">The military prison where Chelsea Manning is beginning her 35-year sentence for espionage has made it clear it will not provide the hormone therapy she is seeking. How difficult is life for transgender people behind bars?</p><p>In July last year a prisoner serving a discretionary life sentence for sexual offences was found hanged at Full Sutton, a maximum security men's jail near York. In the months leading up to the hanging, William "Billie" Evans had been wearing women's clothing and makeup as he became she. Evans was in the process of transitioning into a woman when she died.</p><p>An inquest has not yet been held into the 44-year-old's death, though a prisoner at the jail told the Guardian she had been subjected to intense bullying and had been moved to a supposedly safer wing of the jail when she was found hanging in her single cell.</p><p>But we don't need a coroner to confirm that male prisons are pretty macho places, where bullying is rife. Gyms are the most popular recreational facility, and are usually packed with inmates bent on bulking up their already honed torsos. For gay men, prison presents a challenge: abuse is commonplace, and gay men usually develop a thick skin and a readiness to meet mockery head-on. But those trapped in the wrong gender and undergoing change face an entirely different order of challenge.</p><p>After Bradley Manning was jailed for 35 years this week for leaking a cache of US government secrets, his lawyer, David Coombs, announced that his client wished to be called Chelsea Manning and addressed with the female pronoun. Coombs said Manning was seeking hormone therapy and not a&nbsp;sex-change operation.</p><p>Some jurisdictions in the US now require facilities to provide hormone therapy to trans inmates as a&nbsp;part of their routine medical care, but Fort Leavenworth, the military installation where Manning is being held, is not currently compelled to do the same. Officials there have made it clear that they will not be providing the required treatment, beyond psychiatric support.</p><p>No inmates have received sex-reassignment surgery while in US prisons, Jennifer Levi, director of the Transgender Rights Project for Gay & Lesbian Advocates and Defenders, told NBC News this week. But a 2010 study by the California Department of Corrections and Rehabilitation identified more than 330 transgender inmates in a population of about 160,000, equal to about 0.2%. The National Center for Transgender Equality in the US estimates that the actual figure may be much higher. The&nbsp;prison service in England and Wales&nbsp;says it does not collate figures of transgender prisoners nationally, with a&nbsp;spokeswoman saying simply that "prison staff are required to manage transgendered prisoners in accordance with the law".</p><p>The Scottish Prison Service (SPS), which has a more enlightened policy on trans issues, confirms that in the past year, five prisoners who presented as male when entering the prison system ended up in women's jails, with seven women doing the reverse and ending up in male jails. Currently the Scottish prison population stands at 8,292, (compared with 88,179 in England and&nbsp;Wales), so that is 0.14%.</p><p>In Scotland transgender inmates are identified as soon as they go to jail, says Tom Fox, head of corporate affairs at the SPS. "In all cases, a risk assessment is conducted on arrival at the prison. Thereafter, a multidisciplinary case conference is carried out as soon as possible, [which] will decide on the management of that person. The SPS is&nbsp;developing a policy on gender identity and gender reassignment. Interim guidance developed in conjunction with relevant partners has been issued to staff. The guidance and policy is being developed in partnership with the Transgender Alliance and our legal partners." He is unsure whether any inmates have undergone surgery, but said that the SPS would permit it.</p><p>Ever since the Gender Recognition Act 2004 came into force, prisons in England and Wales have been forced to&nbsp;accommodate the needs of trans inmates who have received legal acknowledgement of their acquired gender through the issue of a gender recognition certificate. A special <a href="http://www.insidetime.org/info-rules-results.asp?rID=492&c=psi2011007_the_care_and_management_of_transsexual_prisoners" title="">prison service order</a> deals with the issue of gender-change prisoners and provides guidance for prison managers and staff. Its main tenet declares establishments must provide prisoners who have been diagnosed with gender dysphoria with the same quality of care they would expect to receive from the NHS if they&nbsp;had not been sent to prison. Jails&nbsp;are instructed to permit prisoners undergoing gender reassignment to live permanently in their acquired gender. This includes dressing in appropriate clothing, adopting new names and form of address. The rules differ according to&nbsp;gender; males wishing to transition to&nbsp;females may be refused permission to&nbsp;transfer to a&nbsp;female prison on grounds of security, but female-to-male prisoners may not be refused a transfer, because there are no grounds that can prevent location in the male estate.</p><p>The position was clarified in <a href="http://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2009/2220.html" title="">a high court judgment</a> in 2009. A pre-operative transgender prisoner at HMP Manchester (formerly Strangeways) asked for a judicial review after being refused a transfer to a female prison on security grounds. The judge, David Elvin QC, ruled that the decision contravened Article 8 of the European Convention on Human Rights and ordered that the claimant be transferred to a female jail. Experts for the prison service and the claimant successfully argued that the Gender Identity Clinic in London would not approve surgery until she had spent a period living as a woman in a&nbsp;female jail. It followed that as long as she remained in the male estate, she was unable to progress towards surgery.</p><p>"The prison service seems to have confused attitudes," the claimant said in evidence. "They will not consider me as a female until I have my penis removed, notwithstanding my gender recognition certificate. Yet they resist moving me to the female estate, which would enable me to have the surgery."</p><p>The 27-year-old said she had been trying to "get this sorted" since she was 10. "It is frustrating not to be able to progress to the final stage, and I worry it&nbsp;may never happen. I get frustrated, but&nbsp;I try to deal with it on my own. I&nbsp;do&nbsp;cry and let my emotions out, but I&nbsp;do this in the privacy of my cell. It is not&nbsp;something I can discuss with anyone&nbsp;in prison."</p><p>As for what will happen to Manning, it is far from clear. LGBT groups in the US declare the military's refusal to provide hormone therapy unconstitutional. But change could be on the horizon. Last year a US judge ruled that the State Department of Correction must provide sex-reassignment surgery for Michelle Kosilek, who is serving a life sentence for murder. <a href="(http://boston.cbslocal.com/2013/04/02/federal-appeals-court-hears-sex-change-case-for-transgender-killer/" title="">Massachusetts prison officials have asked a federal appeals court to overturn the ruling</a>. If Kosilek wins, Manning may be able to expect more compassionate treatment, too.</p><p><em>Additional reporting by Xantha Leatham.</em></p><div class="related" style="float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;"><ul><li><a href="http://www.theguardian.com/world/chelsea-manning">Chelsea Manning (formerly Bradley Manning)</a></li><li><a href="http://www.theguardian.com/media/wikileaks">WikiLeaks</a></li><li><a href="http://www.theguardian.com/world/espionage">Espionage</a></li><li><a href="http://www.theguardian.com/society/transgender">Transgender</a></li><li><a href="http://www.theguardian.com/society/sexuality">Sexuality</a></li><li><a href="http://www.theguardian.com/world/gender">Gender</a></li><li><a href="http://www.theguardian.com/society/prisons-and-probation">Prisons and probation</a></li><li><a href="http://www.theguardian.com/law/criminal-justice">UK criminal justice</a></li><li><a href="http://www.theguardian.com/law/us-constitution-and-civil-liberties">US constitution and civil liberties</a></li><li><a href="http://www.theguardian.com/world/usa">United States</a></li></ul></div><div class="author"><a href="http://www.theguardian.com/profile/ericallison">Eric Allison</a></div><div class="author"><a href="http://www.theguardian.com/profile/helenpidd">Helen Pidd</a></div><br/><div class="terms"><a href="http://www.theguardian.com">theguardian.com</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href="http://www.theguardian.com/help/terms-of-service">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href="http://www.theguardian.com/help/feeds">More Feeds</a></div><p style="clear:both" /><img width='1' height='1' src='http://feeds.theguardian.com/c/34708/f/663879/s/30526d3a/sc/11/mf.gif' border='0'/><br clear='all'/><br/><br/><a href="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/174726131820/u/53/f/663879/c/34708/s/30526d3a/sc/11/rc/1/rc.htm"><img src="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/174726131820/u/53/f/663879/c/34708/s/30526d3a/sc/11/rc/1/rc.img" border="0"/></a><br/><a href="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/174726131820/u/53/f/663879/c/34708/s/30526d3a/sc/11/rc/2/rc.htm"><img src="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/174726131820/u/53/f/663879/c/34708/s/30526d3a/sc/11/rc/2/rc.img" border="0"/></a><br/><a href="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/174726131820/u/53/f/663879/c/34708/s/30526d3a/sc/11/rc/3/rc.htm"><img src="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/174726131820/u/53/f/663879/c/34708/s/30526d3a/sc/11/rc/3/rc.img" border="0"/></a><br/><br/><a href="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/174726131820/u/53/f/663879/c/34708/s/30526d3a/a2.htm"><img src="http://da.feedsportal.com/r/174726131820/u/53/f/663879/c/34708/s/30526d3a/a2.img" border="0"/></a><img width="1" height="1" src="http://pi.feedsportal.com/r/174726131820/u/53/f/663879/c/34708/s/30526d3a/a2t.img" border="0"/>
